<subSubSection id="519F656FFF940443ECF9FD9FFA608D88" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="193A36E4FF940443ECF9FD9FFA608D88" blockId="13.[151,1436,152,1492]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443ECF9FD9FFDF88DC6" bold="true" box="[198,516,615,641]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Distribution and habitat</emphasis>
:—This species is known only from “cerrado” vegetation in the Serra da Petrovina, 
<collectingRegion id="DB41F806FF940443ED29FD76FE4D8DEF" box="[278,433,654,680]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
, central 
<collectingCountry id="61927674FF940443EE2CFD76FDA18DEF" box="[531,605,654,680]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, at an elevation of ca. 
<quantity id="DE7D9B01FF940443EF5BFD76FC4C8DEF" box="[868,944,654,680]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="m" value="500.0">500 m</quantity>
, where it grows terrestrially or rupicolous in reddish soils or on rocky outcrops.. Plants occur solitary, or in groups of a few individuals, across its range.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="519F656FFF940443ECF9FD23FC6F8A93" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="193A36E4FF940443ECF9FD23FACF8C5B" blockId="13.[151,1436,152,1492]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443ECF9FD23FEB18DB2" bold="true" box="[198,333,731,757]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Etymology</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443ED4CFD24FDBF8DB2" authorityName="Leme" authorityYear="2011" box="[371,579,732,757]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kranziana">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443ED4CFD24FDBF8DB2" box="[371,579,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Dyckia kranziana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
honors its collector, the bromeliad (
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443EFCDFD24FB1D8DB2" box="[1010,1249,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Dyckia-Encholirium</emphasis>
) grower Walter Kranz from 
<collectingRegion id="DB41F806FF940443ED19FCFAFE498C5B" box="[294,437,770,796]" country="Brazil" name="Parana" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Paraná state</collectingRegion>
, who has introduced many unusual and new 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443EFFCFCFAFB8E8C5B" box="[963,1138,770,796]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443EFFCFCFAFBEA8C5C" box="[963,1046,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Dyckia</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
into cultivation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="193A36E4FF940443ECF9FCD0FCA48B81" blockId="13.[151,1436,152,1492]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443ECF9FCD0FE908C05" bold="true" box="[198,364,808,834]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Observations</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443EDADFCD1FD988C05" authorityName="Leme" authorityYear="2011" box="[402,612,809,834]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kranziana">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443EDADFCD1FD988C05" box="[402,612,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Dyckia kranziana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443EF34FCD1FB818C04" authority="Mez (1894: 476)" authorityName="Mez" authorityPageNumber="476" authorityYear="1894" box="[779,1149,809,835]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="velascana">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443EF34FCD1FC5B8C05" box="[779,935,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">D. velascana</emphasis>
Mez (1894: 476)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="61927674FF940443E8F4FCD1FABC8C04" box="[1227,1344,809,835]" name="Argentina" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443E940FCD1FEAC8C2D" authority="Mez" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1919" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentella">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443E940FCD1FEE88C2E" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">D. tomentella</emphasis>
Mez
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="61927674FF940443EDA5FCA8FDF68C2D" box="[410,522,848,874]" name="Paraguay" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
. When compared to 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443EF3FFCA8FC678C2E" authorityName="Mez" authorityYear="1894" box="[768,923,848,873]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="velascana">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443EF3FFCA8FC678C2E" box="[768,923,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">D. velascana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this new species differs by the leaf blades with slightly retrorse curved marginal spines (vs. antrorse curved), inflorescence abruptly subspreading near the apex and forming a distinct angle with the erect peduncle (vs. erect or nearly so), floral bracts continuous with the flowers (vs. reflexed) and flowers longer (
<quantity id="DE7D9B01FF940443EED8FC3CFCAB8C99" box="[743,855,964,990]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="7.0">7–15 mm</quantity>
vs. ca. 
<quantity id="DE7D9B01FF940443EF91FC3CFC0C8C99" box="[942,1008,964,990]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
long), and by the sepals without any apical mucro (vs. mucronulate) and completely covered by a dense layer of lanate trichomes (vs. ferruginouspuberulous at base only and glabrous toward the apex). 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443EF03FBE9FBED8B6D" authorityName="Leme" authorityYear="2011" box="[828,1041,1041,1066]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kranziana">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443EF03FBE9FBED8B6D" box="[828,1041,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Dyckia kranziana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has similarities to 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443E8C7FBE9FEA08B15" authority="Mez (1919: 69)" authorityName="Mez" authorityPageNumber="69" authorityYear="1919" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentella">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443E8C7FBE9FA678B6D" box="[1272,1435,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">D. tomentella</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="7D144B15FF940443ECA8FBC0FEA08B15" author="Mez, C." box="[151,348,1080,1106]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refId="ref23192" refString="Mez, C. (1919) Repertorium Specierum Novarum Regni Vegetabilis: 69" type="book" year="1919">Mez (1919: 69)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but it can distinguished from that species by the abruptly subspreading inflorescence, forming a distinct angle with the erect peduncle (vs. erect or nearly so), bearing numerous and densely arranged flowers (vs. sublaxly and few-flowered), floral bracts contiguous with the flowers (vs. subspreading), and by the orange petals (vs. golden yellow).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="193A36E4FF940443ECA8FB2AFC6F8A93" blockId="13.[151,1436,152,1492]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Of the Brazilian species, 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443EDF5FB2BFD9B8BAB" authorityName="Leme" authorityYear="2011" box="[458,615,1235,1260]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kranziana">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443EDF5FB2BFD9B8BAB" box="[458,615,1235,1260]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">D. kranziana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF940443EF46FB2BFAC18BAB" authority="E. Gross &amp; Rauh (1991: 7)" authorityName="E. Gross &amp; Rauh" authorityPageNumber="7" authorityYear="1991" box="[889,1341,1234,1260]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Dyckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="beateae">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF940443EF46FB2BFC008BAB" box="[889,1020,1235,1260]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">D. beateae</emphasis>
E. 
<bibRefCitation id="7D144B15FF940443E824FB2AFAC18BAB" author="Gross, E. &amp; W. Rauh" box="[1051,1341,1234,1260]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref22165" refString="Gross, E. &amp; W. Rauh (1991) Bromelienstudien. I. Neue und wenig bekannte Arten aus Peru und anderen Landern. Abh. Akad. Wiss. Lit. Mainz (Math. - Naturwiss. Klasse) - Tropische und Subtropische Pflanzenwelt 79: 1 - 31." type="journal article" year="1991">Gross &amp; Rauh (1991:7)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, known from Araguainha, 
<collectingRegion id="DB41F806FF940443ED47FB01FDE68A54" box="[376,538,1273,1299]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
. However, this new species can be distinguished from it by the distinctly shorter leaf spines (2.5–5.0 mm vs. 
<quantity id="DE7D9B01FF940443EE78FAD8FD568A7D" box="[583,682,1312,1338]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="mm" value="7.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="6.0">6–9 mm</quantity>
long), inflorescences abruptly subspreading near the apex and forming a distinct angle with the erect peduncle (vs. erect or nearly so), primary branches bearing well developed stipes (vs. sessile or nearly so), sepals densely white-lanate (vs. glabrescent at anthesis and afterwards), and by the stamens equaling to slightly exceeding the petals by a fraction of the anthers (vs. distinctly exceeding the petals with anthers completely exposed).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
